[2]
Date: Thu, 11 Jan 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Eurosurveillance [edited]
<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ew/2007/070111.asp#2>

Four cases of Legionnaires' disease have recently been reported in a
Norwegian, a Finn and 2 people from Sweden. These patients were all
among guests staying at a hotel in Patong Beach, Phuket, Thailand
since 20 Nov 2006. The patients became ill between 6-9 Dec and on 26
Dec 2006. Three cases are in men (aged 24-66) and one is in a woman
(aged 51). None of the cases has been fatal.
The responsible national institutes have informed tour operators with
whom patients traveled about the suspected link to the hotel. Some
tour operators have stopped using the hotel for their guests
temporarily, and all tour operators in Norway, Finland and Sweden who
used the hotel are informing all guests who stayed at the hotel since
20 Nov 2006 by e-mail or post.
Reporting of the individual cases to the European Working Group for
Legionella Infections (EWGLI) resulted in a cluster alert being
issued on the 3 Jan 2006 within the EWGLI network, and to the
International Federation of Tour Operators, World Health Organization
and European Centre for Disease Control (ECDC). Following
confirmation of the 4th case from Norway, an alert was issued to the
Early Warning and Response System on the 9 Jan 2007.
The WHO and ECDC are co-ordinating follow-up of recent visitors to
the hotel who may not have been contacted through tour operators.
Information about the cluster and advice to returning travelers has
been issued on the following national institute websites (National
Public Health Institute Finland: <http://www.ktl.fi>, Norwegian
Institute for Public Health: <http://www.fhi.no>, Swedish Institute
for Infectious Disease Control: <http://www.smittskyddsinstitutet.se>).
Legionnaires' disease (or legionellosis) is a bacterial infection
which presents usually as pneumonia, treatable with antibiotics.
Person to person transmission of the infection has never been
demonstrated. Incubation time is normally 2-10 days. Symptoms include
fever, chills, headache and muscle pain followed by a dry cough and
breathing difficulties associated with the pneumonia.
[Reported by: Lara Payne /1 (<lara.payne@smi.ki.se>, Yvonne Andersson
/1, Luise Ledet Muller /1, Hans Blystad /2, Tran Minh Nhu Nguyen /3,
Petri Ruutu /3, Carol Joseph /4, Katherine Ricketts /4
1/ Smittskyddinstitutet, Solna, Sweden
2/ Folkehelseinstituttet, Oslo, Sweden
3/ Kansanterveyslaitos, Helsinki, Finland
4/ EWGLINET, Centre for Infections, Health Protection Agency,
London, United Kingdom]
